description:

From Colleen Hoover, the best-selling author of It Ends With Us. Only in theaters March 13.

There was before you and there was during you. For some reason, I never thought there would be an after you.

The literary phenomenon from #1 New York Times bestselling author Colleen Hoover becomes a transformative feature film about motherhood, forgiveness and the power of love to overcome even the worst mistake. 

After a perfect outing with her boyfriend, Kenna (Maika Monroe; The Hand that Rocks the Cradle, Longlegs) makes an unbearable mistake that sends her to prison. Seven years later, Kenna returns to her hometown in Wyoming, hoping to rebuild her life and earn the chance to reunite with her young daughter, Diem, whom she has never known. 

When Diem‚Äôs custodial grandparents adamantly refuse Kenna‚Äôs attempts to see her daughter, Kenna discovers unexpected compassion, and then something truer and deeper, with former NFL player and local bar owner Ledger (Tyriq Withers; HIM, I Know What You Did Last Summer). As their secret romance develops, so do the dangers for both of them, leading Kenna toward heartbreak and, ultimately, the hope for a second chance. 

The film‚Äôs cast includes screen legends Lauren Graham (Gilmore Girls, Zoey‚Äôs Extraordinary Playlist) and three-time Emmy winner Bradley Whitford (Get Out, The Handmaid‚Äôs Tale) as Diem‚Äôs grandparents, Grace and Patrick; Rudy Pankow (Outer Banks, Uncharted) as Scotty, Diem‚Äôs father; and Grammy winner and country music sensation Lainey Wilson (Yellowstone) as Kenna‚Äôs friend and coworker, Amy. 

The supporting cast includes Jennifer Robertson (Schitt‚Äôs Creek) as Kenna‚Äôs landlord; Zoe Kosovic (The Smashing Machine) as Kenna‚Äôs daughter; Hilary Jardine (Holidazed) and Nicholas Duvernay (The White Lotus) as Ledger‚Äôs bar team; and, in her screen debut, Monika Myers as Kenna‚Äôs neighbor, Lady Diana. 

Leading an all-female filmmaking team, Vanessa Caswill (Love at First Sight, Little Women mini-series) directs Reminders of Him from a screenplay by Colleen Hoover and Lauren Levine, based on Hoover‚Äôs novel. The film is produced by Colleen Hoover (exec producer It Ends with Us, Regretting You), Lauren Levine (Bridge to Terabithia, exec producer, Confess series) and Gina Matthews (Isn‚Äôt it Romantic, 13 Going on 30), and is executive produced by Robin Mulcahy Fisichella. Universal Pictures presents a Heartbones Entertainment and Little Engine production: Reminders of Him.

First published in 2022, Reminders of Him has sold more than 6 million copies in the United States and has been translated into 45 languages. Hoover is the bestselling author of numerous blockbuster novels, including It Ends with Us, It Starts with Us,  Layla, Heart Bones, Confess and Verity.

title: Minecraft Speedrunner Swap VS 2 Hunters REMATCH
description:
This was crazy intense. Manhunt, but with a twist.

This video, I teamed up with a Manhunt NOOB, Dr Donut, in a new #MinecraftManhunt challenge. We have to speedrun and beat Minecraft against two hunters, but we swap who is playing every minute! It was hilarious and super intense. This is the REMATCH, what was not uploaded to my main channel.

Follow my socials:
‚ûΩ Twitter - @dreamwastaken
‚ûΩ Instagram - @dreamwastaken
‚ûΩ Snapchat - @dreampublic


In this challenge Dr Donut and I essentially are one player. We share an inventory, health, position, and basically everything else. The idea is that we are swapping who has control of one player. When we are swapped out, we don't know what is happening at all. We see a black screen and hear nothing.

This is one of my first ever collabs of this type, if you'd like to see more, like the video!

This was played on Minecraft 1.21.8, and is a custom coded challenge. There were a few bugs that we plan to iron out before we try something like this again!

description:
So many people keep calling the music in KPop Demon Hunters generic, but most don‚Äôt realize there‚Äôs something hidden in each of the songs that proves they‚Äôre not as basic as they might seem. Beneath the surface, the soundtrack is packed with clever details, subtle callbacks, and even mistakes that turned into genius moments.

Take Soda Pop by the Saja Boys ‚Äî the vocals suddenly disappear to reveal that ‚ÄúBaby Saja‚Äù is rapping over a literal nursery rhyme, I‚Äôm a Little Teapot. Then there‚Äôs Golden by Huntr/x, which doesn‚Äôt just stand alone as a song, but actually appears in multiple variations across the entire movie‚Äôs soundtrack, weaving itself into the film‚Äôs musical DNA.

But the two cleverest hidden moments both come from another Huntr/x track. At first, you hear the lyric ‚ÄúI see your real face and it‚Äôs ugly as sin,‚Äù which sounds like a throwaway mistake ‚Äî but in reality, it‚Äôs Mira accidentally singing Zoey‚Äôs line. This small slip makes perfect sense once you realize that both characters are demons in disguise. And speaking of demons, there‚Äôs a reason why Rumi‚Äôs delivery of ‚ÄúA demon with no feelings don‚Äôt deserve to live‚Äù was changed from the studio version to the one used in the movie ‚Äî a change that carries much deeper meaning than you might expect.

title: No One Noticed This About the K-Pop Demon Hunters Songs.. üòàü§î #music  #kpop
description:
So many people keep calling the music in KPop Demon Hunters generic, but most don‚Äôt realize there‚Äôs something hidden in each of the songs that proves they‚Äôre not as basic as they might seem. Beneath the surface, the soundtrack is packed with clever details, subtle callbacks, and even mistakes that turned into genius moments.

Take Soda Pop by the Saja Boys ‚Äî the vocals suddenly disappear to reveal that ‚ÄúBaby Saja‚Äù is rapping over a literal nursery rhyme, I‚Äôm a Little Teapot. Then there‚Äôs Golden by Huntr/x, which doesn‚Äôt just stand alone as a song, but actually appears in multiple variations across the entire movie‚Äôs soundtrack, weaving itself into the film‚Äôs musical DNA.

But the two cleverest hidden moments both come from another Huntr/x track. At first, you hear the lyric ‚ÄúI see your real face and it‚Äôs ugly as sin,‚Äù which sounds like a throwaway mistake ‚Äî but in reality, it‚Äôs Mira accidentally singing Zoey‚Äôs line. This small slip makes perfect sense once you realize that both characters are demons in disguise. And speaking of demons, there‚Äôs a reason why Rumi‚Äôs delivery of ‚ÄúA demon with no feelings don‚Äôt deserve to live‚Äù was changed from the studio version to the one used in the movie ‚Äî a change that carries much deeper meaning than you might expect.

Kehlani‚Äôs 2015 breakout mixtape You Should Be Here received a 2016 GRAMMY¬Æ Award nod in the category of ‚ÄúBest Urban Contemporary Album.‚Äù On its heels, her 2017 full-length debut SweetSexySavage bowed at #3 on the Billboard Top 200 and eventually went gold. Between selling out dates on the SweetSexySavage Tour, the record closed out the year on Pitchfork‚Äôs ‚ÄúThe 50 Best Albums of 2017‚Äù and Rolling Stone‚Äôs ‚Äú20 Best R&B Albums of 2017.‚Äù

By 2020, she picked up three gold solo singles‚Äî"You Should Be Here,‚Äù ‚ÄúHoney,‚Äù and ‚ÄúDistraction,‚Äù for which she received her second GRAMMY¬Æ nomination for Best R&B performance. title: No One Noticed This About the K-Pop Demon Hunters Songs.. üòàü§î #music  #kpop
description:
So many people keep calling the music in KPop Demon Hunters generic, but most don‚Äôt realize there‚Äôs something hidden in each of the songs that proves they‚Äôre not as basic as they might seem. Beneath the surface, the soundtrack is packed with clever details, subtle callbacks, and even mistakes that turned into genius moments.

Take Soda Pop by the Saja Boys ‚Äî the vocals suddenly disappear to reveal that ‚ÄúBaby Saja‚Äù is rapping over a literal nursery rhyme, I‚Äôm a Little Teapot. Then there‚Äôs Golden by Huntr/x, which doesn‚Äôt just stand alone as a song, but actually appears in multiple variations across the entire movie‚Äôs soundtrack, weaving itself into the film‚Äôs musical DNA.

But the two cleverest hidden moments both come from another Huntr/x track. At first, you hear the lyric ‚ÄúI see your real face and it‚Äôs ugly as sin,‚Äù which sounds like a throwaway mistake ‚Äî but in reality, it‚Äôs Mira accidentally singing Zoey‚Äôs line. This small slip makes perfect sense once you realize that both characters are demons in disguise. And speaking of demons, there‚Äôs a reason why Rumi‚Äôs delivery of ‚ÄúA demon with no feelings don‚Äôt deserve to live‚Äù was changed from the studio version to the one used in the movie ‚Äî a change that carries much deeper meaning than you might expect.
